	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">He's not talking about page tearing from what I understand. He's talking about a strange effect on LCDs where things look normal until you begin scrolling and then there is this fuzzy/blurring effect. It stops when you stop scrolling. I've noticed it sometimes.</div>
<br />Some color LCDs have a pattern similar to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_crawl" class="postlink">dot crawl on an NTSC composite video image</a>, only it's over all areas, not just around the edges of objects.  See the inversion section of <a href="http://www.techmind.org/lcd/" class="postlink">LCD technology and tests</a>, left illustration where it's a checkerboard pattern. When an image is scrolling, the pattern becomes more visible.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
